dict'' (1977)\n* ''Najdolgiot pat'' (1977)\n* ''Beliot sid'' (1978)\n* ''Kliment Ohridski'' (1986)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KHpKIyZwly0 YouTube, (''Sonata for two pianos Op.&nbsp;122 (1990)'')]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ao3ik2CuXdw YouTube, (''Siyaniem for soloist and mixed choir Op.&nbsp;74 (1972)'')]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zografski, Tomislav}}\n[[Category:Macedonian composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Composers for piano]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical composers]]\n\n{{Composer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SpookiePuppy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Removing brackets from both titles in external links; Moving the italics to only affect the title; adding commas after titles.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tomislav_Zografski"}
{"title_page": "Ayyathan Gopalan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ayyathan Gopalan \n| image              = DR. Ayathan Gopalan.png\n| caption            = Gopalan Darsarji\n| birth_name         = Ayyathan Gopalan\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1861|03|03}}\n| birth_place        = Thalassery, Chettamkunnu (Pulappadi Illam)\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1948|05|02|1861|03|03}}\n| death_place        = Calicut Shanthi Ashram\n| spouse             = {{marriage |Kallat Kausallya|1878|1930}}\n| children           = {{plainlist}}\n*Dr. A. Chandramohan\n*Dr. Capt. Rev. A. Bhuvanadas\n*A. Sarojabainivas\n*A. Devadath\n*A. Balgopal\n{{endplainlist}}\n| alma_mater         = [[Madras Medical College]]\n| occupation         = Doctor, Chief Surgeon, Medical School Professor (Mainly known for Social reformation)\n| known_for          = Physician, Writing, Philanthropy, Social reform in Kerala\n| relatives          = {{plainlist}}\n*Dr. Janaki Ayathan (First Lady Doctor of Malabar)\n*Madhavi Ayathan\n*Kunjiraman Ayathan\n{{endplainlist}}\n| awards             = [[Rai Sahib]]\n}}\n'''Rao Sahib Dr. Ayyathan Gopalan''', popularly known as '''Darsarji''', \"doctor\", was an Indian physician, writer, social reformer, and philanthropist. He is known mainly for being the pioneer of [[Brahmo Samaj]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830,.|last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=[[Funk & Wagnalls]]|oclc=1032604831}}</ref> and as the founder of the Sugunavardhini movement in [[Kerala]]. He denounced idol worship and fought to end those social practices he thought were unethical, but prevalent, in Kerala. Among his favorite disciples were [[Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Biography of Brahmananda swami Sivayogy by A K Nair|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi by Pavanan|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Biography of Brahmanada Sivayogi written by K Bheeman Nair \"Asathyathil ninnu sathyathilekku\"(\u0d05\u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d )|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi and His Selected Works by P.V. Gopalakrishnan|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sreyas.in/brahmananda-sivayogi|title=sivayogi|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kerala Navothanam - Oru Marxist Veekshanam - P. Govindappilla (Chintha Publishers, Thiruvananthapuram-695001)|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi and his selected works|last=Gopalakrishnan, P. V.|date=2002|publisher=Kalpaz Publications|isbn=8178351013|oclc=52726748}}</ref> [[Vagbhatananda|Vaghbatananda]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kurup, K. K. N. (1988), Modern Kerala: Studies in Social and Agrarian Relations, Mittal Publications, ISBN 9788170990949|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Shepherds' Chalet, Shepherds' Chalet, Shepherdschalet.com, retrieved 19 March 2014|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Kurup, K. K. N. (September 1988). \"Peasantry and the Anti-Imperialist Struggles in Kerala\". Social Scientist. 16 (9): 35\u201345. doi:10.2307/3517171. JSTOR 3517171.|journal=Social Scientist|volume=16|issue=9|pages=35\u201345|year=1988|url-status=live|doi=10.2307/3517171|jstor=3517171|last1=Kurup|first1=K. K. N.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vagbhatananda-admavidya.com/|title=Vagbhatananda|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Mahar\u1e63i V\u0101gba\u1e6d\u0101nanda Gurud\u0113var.|last=Brahmavrathan, Swami.|date=1971|oclc=978079481}}</ref> and Brahmavadhi [[P. Kunhiraman Nair|P. Kunhiraman]]. Gopalan honored Swami Sivayogi and P. Kunhiraman with the titles \"Brahmananda\" and \"Brahmavadi\", respectively, for their involvement in promoting social services through Brahmo Samaj. He also initiated the Sugunavardhini movement, which played a significant role in the [[Kerala reformation movement]].\n\n==Biography==\nGopalan was born into the [[Ayathan School|Ayyathan]] family of Pulappadi Illam (Aristocratic Thiyya family of Malabar) in Chettamkunnu, [[Thalassery]], (formerly Telicherry), Kerala. He was the first son of Ayyathan Chandhan and Kallat Chiruthammal. His grandfather, Ayyathan Kannan Vaidyar, was a noted [[Ayurvedic]] physician in Thalassery, who was well versed in the treatment of intoxication and was also a [[Kalaripayattu|Kalari]] [[Gurukkal (kalaripayattu)|Gurukkal]]. His youngest sister, Ayyathan Janakiammal, was the first female doctor in Malabar, Kerala.\n\nHe attended [[Government Brennen College, Thalassery|Brennen School]] and [[Mission school|Mission High School]] and later joined [[Madras Medical College]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Annual Report of the Madras Medical College. Session 1855-56( -1876-77).|last=Madras Medical College.|date=1856\u201377|oclc=562478204}}</ref> on 19&nbsp;September 1884. During his college years, he was introduced to the principles of Brahmo Samaj and [[Ram Mohan Roy|Raja Ram Mohan Roy]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nazir|first=Parwez|date=2011|title=Raja Ram Mohan Roy: Social Reform and Empowerment of Women|journal=Journal of Exclusion Studies|volume=1|issue=2|pages=1|doi=10.5958/j.2231-4547.1.2.013|issn=2231-4547}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Sati, a writeup of Raja Ram Mohan Roy about burning of widows alive|last=Rammohun Roy, Raja, 1772?-1833.|date=1996|publisher=B.R. Pub. Corp|isbn=8170188989|oclc=38110572}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hatcher|first=Brian A.|title=Debendranath Tagore and the Tattvabodhin\u012b Sabh\u0101|date=2008-01-01|work=Bourgeouis Hinduism, or Faith of the Modern Vedantists|pages=33\u201348|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780195326086|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195326086.003.0003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Men I have seen; personal reminiscences of seven great Bengalis.|last=\u015a\u0101str\u012b, \u015aiban\u0101tha, 1847-1919.|date=1948|publisher=Sadharan Brahmo Samaj|oclc=11057931}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Killingley|first=Dermot|chapter=Rammohun Roy and the Bengal Renaissance|date=2019-06-27|pages=36\u201353|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198790839|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198790839.003.0003|title=The Oxford History of Hinduism: Modern Hinduism}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Reflections on the Bengal renaissance : [papers read at a seminar, \"Perspectives of the Bengal Renaissance\"]|last=Seminar on Perspectives of the Bengal Renaissance (1976 : Rajshahi University)|date=1977|publisher=Institute of Bangladesh Studies, Rajshahi University|oclc=557887410}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|chapter=Rabindranath Tagore: His Life and Thought|date=2016-02-24|pages=1\u201317|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781315554709|doi=10.4324/9781315554709-1|title=The Philosophy of Rabindranath Tagore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830,.|last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|oclc=1032604831}}</ref> At this time, he became involved in social activities. He was an active executive member of the General Committee of Calcutta Brahmo Samaj since his college days. He participated in the committee's annual conferences at various locations across India, along with Brahmo leaders such as [[Keshub Chandra Sen|Kesub Chandra Sen]], [[Debendranath Tagore]], Sivanath Sastri, [[Rabindranath Tagore]], [[R. G. Bhandarkar]], and others. In 1888, he obtained a medical degree with honors and entered into [[Public service|government service]]. After that, he worked as a [[medic]] in several hospitals across South India and as a medical lecturer. He also served as a magistrate during the [[British rule]] in Malabar.\n\nGopalan married Kallat Kausallyaammal on 30&nbsp;December 1894. According to the rituals involved, this was the first Brahmo wedding. Ramakrishna Gobal Bhandhakar, a Brahmo leader and social reformer at that time, conducted the wedding at the Madras Brahmo Samaj. Several Brahmo leaders presided over the wedding. Kallat Kausallyaammal was a supporter of Gopalan and assisted his social reform activities.\n\nGopalan worked as a doctor, chief surgeon, and [[Chief physician|superintendent]] at several hospitals in [[South India]], including in [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]], [[Tiruchirappalli|Tiruchirapalli]], [[Madurai]], [[Chennai]], [[Mysore]], and [[Bangalore]] ([[Bowring & Lady Curzon Hospitals]]). He returned to Kerala in 1896 and joined [[Kuthiravattam Mental Hospital|Calicut Lunatic asylum]] (now the Kuthiravattom Mental Hospital) as its first superintendent. Meanwhile, [[caste]] and [[racial discrimination]], evil practices, beliefs, and social injustices were prevalent in Kerala, and atrocities against women and children were at their peak. Gopalan extended his reform ideologies and propagated his reform activities by establishing Brahmo Samaj<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830, |last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|oclc=1032604831}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Brahmo-Samaj|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebrahmosamaj.net|title=brahmosamajnet|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebrahmosamaj.net/history/history.html|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adaniel.tripod.com/brahmosamaj.htm|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> on 17&nbsp;January 1898 at [[Kozhikode|Calicut]]. To conduct Samaj meetings and prayers, a separate Brahmomandir (hall), now the Ayathan Gopalan Memorial School, Calicut, was opened to the public on 17&nbsp;October 1900. The Brahmomandir was inaugurated by [[Zamorin of Calicut|Mana Vikraman Ettan Thampuran]], the Zamorin King<ref>{{Cite book|title=The zamorins of Calicut: from the earliest times down to A.D. 1806|last=Krishna Ayyar, K. V., 1894-|date=1999|publisher=Publication Division, University of Calicut|oclc=607834506}}</ref> of Calicut. The second branch of Brahmo Samaj was established at [[Alappuzha]] in 1924. A Brahmomandir was also constructed in 1928 at: Poonthoppu, Kommady, Alappuzha (now Grihalakshmi Gandhi Smaraka Seva Sangam) with the donation by a [[landlord]] ([[Jenmi]]) of Alleppey, named Mangalath Cochoumini Channar. Channar was once a strict follower of [[Narayana Guru|Sree Narayana Guru]], but was later influenced by the reform activities of Gopalan and Brahmo Samaj. His daughter, Mangalath Cochoumini Mandhakinibai, spearheaded the reform activities at Alappuzha Brahmosamaj and was married to Gopalan's third son, Devadath Ayathan. This was the first Brahmo wedding conducted at Alappuzha Brahmo Samaj, which spread the custom of Misra Vivaham all over South Kerala.\n\nIn the year 1900, Gopalan initiated the Sugunavardhini Movement and began his social reform activities. Through this movement, he worked to foster human values in children, protect the rights of women, and provide free education to girls and marginalized sections of society, especially the [[Harijan]] communities in Kerala, that were then ill-treated by the higher castes, such as the [[Brahmin]]s and the [[Nair]]s. He established the Lady Chandhawarkar Elementary School intending to educate girls and the underprivileged section of society. Weekly meetings were conducted at his home, Santhi Ashram. Women, children, and people from all walks of life gathered there to share their sorrows with Gopalan and Kausallyaammal, who worked to address them. Children were offered an opportunity to showcase their talents and skills, and were appreciated during these weekly meetings. Kausallyaammal, along with her daughter-in-law M.C. Mandhakinibai Devadath, united women and the lower sections of the community to help them assert their social rights.\n\nUnlike the [[Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana Yogam|Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana (SNDP)]], which had been established by Narayana Guru<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sreenarayanaguru.in/|title=narayana guru|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; \u1e62\u0101j\u012b, K. N. (2002). N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru: j\u012bvita\u1e43 kr\u0325tika\u1e37 dar\u015bana\u1e43. Tr\u032e\u015b\u015b\u016br: Kar\u0332ant\u0332 Buks: Distribution Cosmo Books. OCLC 52929384.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; B\u0101lakr\u0325i\u1e63h\u1e47an, P. K. (1969). N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru (in Malayalam). Kottayam: Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative : Society Ltd. OCLC 31116295.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana, Guru; Nityachaitanya, Yati (2003). That alone, the core of wisdom: a commentary on \u0100tmopade\u015ba \u015batakam, the one hundred verses of self-instruction of Narayana Guru. New Delhi: D.K. Printworld. ISBN 9788124602409. OCLC 915135852.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru (1961). Souvenir to commemorate the 107th birthday of Sree Narayana Guru. Singapore: Sree Narayana Mission. OCLC 498088723.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; Kesavan Vaidyar, C. R (1990). \u015ar\u0332\u012bn\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru Svantha\u1e43 Vachana\u1e45ga\u1e37iloode (in Malayalam). K\u014d\u1e6d\u1e6daya\u1e43: \u1e0ci. \u1e62i. Buks: Distributors, Current Books. OCLC 27111533|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=A prophet of peace or Sree Narayana Gurudev of labor (a study).|last=Theerthan, Swami Dharma.|date=1933|publisher=The City Press|oclc=78599841}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Garland of visions : Dar\u015banam\u0101l\u0101 of Narayana Guru|last=Narayana Guru, 1856-1928.|date=2007|publisher=D.K. Printworld|isbn=978-8124603918|oclc=167576536}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Narayana Guru|doi = 10.1163/2212-5019_beh_com_9000000256}}</ref> and was influential around the same time, the Sugunavardhini Movement and Brahmo Samaj were composed mostly of professionals and intellectuals, including Brahmananda Swamisivayogi, Vagbhatananda Guru, and Brahmavadi P. Kunhiraman, all with a more secular approach to reform. Other eminent personalities who worked with Brahmo Samaj Calicut were: G. Subbha Rao, Kallingal Madathil Rarichan Mooppan, Kunjikoru Mooppan, C. Achuthan Vakeel, B.S.T. Mudaliyar, Rao Bahadur V. V. Govindan, Kallat Raghavan, Swami Aryabhadhan, Swami Brahmavradhan, Padmanabha Panikar, Sadhu Sivaprasad, Rama Sasthrikal, Manjeri Ramayyar, [[Mithavaadi Krishnan|Mithavadi C. Krishnan]], Lady Chandhawarkar, Rabindranath Tagore, Kesub Chandrasen, [[Rajnarayan Basu|Raj Narayan Basu]], [[Ramananda Chatterjee|Ramananda Chatterji]], Debjyothi Burman, Sasi Bhushan Basu, Satishchandra Chakraborthi, Jatheendrakumar Majumdar, and [[Mahadev Govind Ranade|Justice Ranade]]. In addition to uplifting the underprivileged and the marginalized, and educating women and [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|the underprivileged]], their movement led to several reforms, such as Misra Vivaham and Misra Bhojanam. Dr. Gopalan also took part in the Thali Road strike (Samaram at Calicut).\n\nOn 17&nbsp;November 1917, Gopalan was honored by the British Government with the highest civilian award and title, [[Rai Sahib|Rao Sahib]],<ref>\"British India: INDIAN TITLE BADGE (MYB # 327), RAO BAHADUR & RAO SAHIB MEDALS\". worldofcoins.eu. Retrieved 2014-10-18.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omsa.org/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=65&size=big&cat=|title=rai sahib|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omsa.org/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=65&size=big&cat=|title=medal|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldofcoins.eu/forum/index.php?topic=21524.0|title=rao sahib|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Introduction to the Constitution of India By Sharma, Sharma B.k.. 2007. p. 83.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kaur, Madanjit (2008). Maharaja Ranjit Singh. Unistar Books. ISBN 9788189899547.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref> for his social and humanitarian services.\n\nHe passed away on 2&nbsp;May 1948, at the age of 87.\n\n==Works==\nGopalan translated the Bible of Brahmosamaj, [[Brahmo Dharma|Brahmodharma]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The offering. [Reprinted on the occasion of the centenary celebration of Maharshideva's initiation into the Brahma Dharma].|last=\u1e6ch\u0101kura, Debendran\u0101tha, 1817-1905.|date=c. 1943|oclc=910095}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hatcher|first=Brian A.|title=Debendranath Tagore and the Tattvabodhin\u012b Sabh\u0101|date=2008-01-01|work=Bourgeouis Hinduism, or Faith of the Modern Vedantists|pages=33\u201348|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195326086|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195326086.003.0003}}</ref> initially  written in the [[Bengali language]] by Maharshi Debendranath Tagore, to Malayalam in 1910. He also wrote many songs and [[Kirtan|keerthanams]] to be sung during [[Brahmoism|Brahmosamaj prayer]] meetings. He propagated his reform ideologies through drama, public awareness, and his writings. ''Saranjiniparinayam'', ''Susheeladukham'' (musical drama), and ''Plaguefarse'' were among his famous dramas performed by the [[Vaidyaratnam P. S. Warrier|Kottakkal P. S. Warrier]] Nadaka Sangam throughout Kerala for many years. His other literary contributions are listed below:\n\n* ''Brahmadharmam''\n* ''Keerthanaratnamala''\n* ''Brahmamatham''\n* ''Rammohunroy (Harikatha)''\n* ''Madhaaikyam''\n* ''Madhavum Guruvum''\n* ''Madhavan''\n* ''Aaradhanayude Randu Padikal''\n* ''Brahma Madhavum Ithara Madhangalum''\n* ''Jaathi''\n* ''Plague Farse'' (drama)\n* ''Vivaahageethangal''\n* ''Saranjiniparinayam'' (musical drama)\n* ''Susheeladukham'' (musical drama)\n* ''Jai Britannia''\n* ''Yeshu Daivamayirunnuvo''\n* ''British Bharana Mahathmyam''\n* ''Ente Ammayude Ormadaykk'' (biography of mother Kallat Chiruthammal)\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Dr. Ayyathan Gopalan  ''Malayalam Memoir'' (2013) edited by V.R.Govindhanunni published by Mathrubhumi books, Kozhikode\n* Kesava Menon. K. P. (1974). ''Samakaleenaraya Chila Keraleeyar''. Sahithya Pra. Co. s: Sahithya Pra. Co. s. p.&nbsp;239\n* Kausallya Gopalan (1932) Biography written by [[Vagbhatananda]] guru, published by Mathrubhumi Press, Calicut in 1932\n* ''Mughaparichayam'' (1959) Govindan A.C. Published by K.R.Brothers, Kozhikkode. p.&nbsp;155 p.&nbsp;156 p.&nbsp;157 p.&nbsp;158 p.&nbsp;159\n* ''Ente ammayude ormadaykk'' (1901) Biography of Kallat Chiruthammal, written by DR.Ayathan Gopalan.\n* Prof. Sreedharan Menon .A. (1967). ''A Survey of Kerala History''. Kottayam: Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative Society [Sales Dept.]; National Book Stall.\n* Prof.Sreedharamenon .A. (1987) ''Kerala History and its Makers'', Kottayam; National bookstall\n* [[K. K. N. Kurup|Kurup, K. K. N.]] (1988), ''Modern Kerala: Studies in Social and Agrarian Relations'', Mittal Publications, {{ISBN|9788170990949}}\n* [[Vagbhatananda#CITEREFKurup1988|Kurup (1988)]], p.&nbsp;94\n* [[K. K. N. Kurup|Kurup, K. K. N.]] (September 1988). \"Peasantry and the Anti-Imperialist Struggles in Kerala\". ''Social Scientist''. '''16''' (9): 35\u201345. {{doi|10.2307/3517171}}. {{JSTOR|3517171}}.\n* Biography of Brahmanada Sivayogi written by K Bheeman Nair ''Asathyathil ninnu sathyathilekku''(\u0d05\u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d )\n* ''Biography of Brahmananda Swami Sivayogy'' by A K Nair\n* ''Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi'' by Pavana\n*''Journal of Indian history'', University of Kerela Press, 2001 p270\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayyathan Gopalan}}\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Brahmoism]]\n[[Category:Indian medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Indian writers]]\n[[Category:People from Kerala]]\n[[Category:People from Thalassery]]\n[[Category:Reform movements]]\n[[Category:Social reformers]]\n", "text_old": "<br />\n[[File:Appan.jpg|163x163px|alt=|border|left]]{{Reformation in Kerala}}{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = RaoSahib\n| name               = Dr. Ayyathan Gopalan\n| image              = appan.jpg\n| native_name        = \u0d21\u0d4b. \u0d05\u0d2f\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3e\u0d7b \u0d17\u0d4b\u0d2a\u0d3e\u0d32\u0d7b\n| other_names        = Darsarji\n| birth_date         = 1861 March 3\n| birth_place        = Thalassery, Chettamkunnu\n| death_date         = 1948 May 2\n| death_place        = Calicut, Santhi ashram\n| resting_place      = Ayathan family cemetry, Santhi gardens\n| alma_mater         = Madras medical college\n| occupation         = Doctor, Chief surgeon, Medical school Professor\n| known_for          = Social reformer of Kerala\n| notable_works      = Brahmodarma malayalam(Bible of bhramosamaj)\nSaranjiniparinayam(musical drama)\nSusheeladukham(musical drama)\n| title              = RaoSahib\n| movement           = Sugunavardhini movement\n| spouse             = Kallat Kausallyaammal\n| children           = Dr. Chandramohan Ayathan\nDr. Bhuvanadas Ayathan\nSarojabainivas\n\nDevadath Ayathan\nBalgopal Ayathan\n| mother             = Kallat Chiruthammal\n| father             = Ayyathan Chandhan\n| relatives          = Dr. Janakiammal Ayathan (First lady doctor of Malabar region, Kerala)\nMadhaviammal Ayathan\nKunjiraman Ayathan\n| honours            = Raosahib (Highest civilian award of India during British rule)\n}}\n'''Rao Sahib Dr. Ayyathan Gopalan''', popularly known as '''Darsarji''', \"doctor\", was an Indian physician, writer, social reformer, and philanthropist. He is known mainly for being the pioneer of [[Brahmo Samaj]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830,.|last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=[[Funk & Wagnalls]]|oclc=1032604831}}</ref> and as the founder of the Sugunavardhini movement in [[Kerala]]. He denounced idol worship and fought to end those social practices he thought were unethical, but prevalent, in Kerala. Among his favorite disciples were [[Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Biography of Brahmananda swami Sivayogy by A K Nair|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi by Pavanan|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Biography of Brahmanada Sivayogi written by K Bheeman Nair \"Asathyathil ninnu sathyathilekku\"(\u0d05\u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d )|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi and His Selected Works by P.V. Gopalakrishnan|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sreyas.in/brahmananda-sivayogi|title=sivayogi|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kerala Navothanam - Oru Marxist Veekshanam - P. Govindappilla (Chintha Publishers, Thiruvananthapuram-695001)|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi and his selected works|last=Gopalakrishnan, P. V.|date=2002|publisher=Kalpaz Publications|isbn=8178351013|oclc=52726748}}</ref> [[Vagbhatananda|Vaghbatananda]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kurup, K. K. N. (1988), Modern Kerala: Studies in Social and Agrarian Relations, Mittal Publications, ISBN 9788170990949|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Shepherds' Chalet, Shepherds' Chalet, Shepherdschalet.com, retrieved 19 March 2014|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Kurup, K. K. N. (September 1988). \"Peasantry and the Anti-Imperialist Struggles in Kerala\". Social Scientist. 16 (9): 35\u201345. doi:10.2307/3517171. JSTOR 3517171.|journal=Social Scientist|volume=16|issue=9|pages=35\u201345|year=1988|url-status=live|doi=10.2307/3517171|jstor=3517171|last1=Kurup|first1=K. K. N.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vagbhatananda-admavidya.com/|title=Vagbhatananda|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Mahar\u1e63i V\u0101gba\u1e6d\u0101nanda Gurud\u0113var.|last=Brahmavrathan, Swami.|date=1971|oclc=978079481}}</ref> and Brahmavadhi [[P. Kunhiraman Nair|P. Kunhiraman]]. Gopalan honored Swami Sivayogi and P. Kunhiraman with the titles \"Brahmananda\" and \"Brahmavadi\", respectively, for their involvement in promoting social services through Brahmo Samaj. He also initiated the Sugunavardhini movement, which played a significant role in the [[Kerala reformation movement]].\n\n==Biography==\nGopalan was born into the [[Ayathan School|Ayyathan]] family of Pulappadi Illam (Aristocratic Thiyya family of Malabar) in Chettamkunnu, [[Thalassery]], (formerly Telicherry), Kerala. He was the first son of Ayyathan Chandhan and Kallat Chiruthammal. His grandfather, Ayyathan Kannan Vaidyar, was a noted [[Ayurvedic]] physician in Thalassery, who was well versed in the treatment of intoxication and was also a [[Kalaripayattu|Kalari]] [[Gurukkal (kalaripayattu)|Gurukkal]]. His youngest sister, Ayyathan Janakiammal, was the first female doctor in Malabar, Kerala.\n\nHe attended [[Government Brennen College, Thalassery|Brennen School]] and [[Mission school|Mission High School]] and later joined [[Madras Medical College]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Annual Report of the Madras Medical College. Session 1855-56( -1876-77).|last=Madras Medical College.|date=1856\u201377|oclc=562478204}}</ref> on 19&nbsp;September 1884. During his college years, he was introduced to the principles of Brahmo Samaj and [[Ram Mohan Roy|Raja Ram Mohan Roy]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nazir|first=Parwez|date=2011|title=Raja Ram Mohan Roy: Social Reform and Empowerment of Women|journal=Journal of Exclusion Studies|volume=1|issue=2|pages=1|doi=10.5958/j.2231-4547.1.2.013|issn=2231-4547}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Sati, a writeup of Raja Ram Mohan Roy about burning of widows alive|last=Rammohun Roy, Raja, 1772?-1833.|date=1996|publisher=B.R. Pub. Corp|isbn=8170188989|oclc=38110572}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hatcher|first=Brian A.|title=Debendranath Tagore and the Tattvabodhin\u012b Sabh\u0101|date=2008-01-01|work=Bourgeouis Hinduism, or Faith of the Modern Vedantists|pages=33\u201348|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780195326086|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195326086.003.0003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Men I have seen; personal reminiscences of seven great Bengalis.|last=\u015a\u0101str\u012b, \u015aiban\u0101tha, 1847-1919.|date=1948|publisher=Sadharan Brahmo Samaj|oclc=11057931}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Killingley|first=Dermot|chapter=Rammohun Roy and the Bengal Renaissance|date=2019-06-27|pages=36\u201353|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198790839|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198790839.003.0003|title=The Oxford History of Hinduism: Modern Hinduism}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Reflections on the Bengal renaissance : [papers read at a seminar, \"Perspectives of the Bengal Renaissance\"]|last=Seminar on Perspectives of the Bengal Renaissance (1976 : Rajshahi University)|date=1977|publisher=Institute of Bangladesh Studies, Rajshahi University|oclc=557887410}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|chapter=Rabindranath Tagore: His Life and Thought|date=2016-02-24|pages=1\u201317|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781315554709|doi=10.4324/9781315554709-1|title=The Philosophy of Rabindranath Tagore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830,.|last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|oclc=1032604831}}</ref> At this time, he became involved in social activities. He was an active executive member of the General Committee of Calcutta Brahmo Samaj since his college days. He participated in the committee's annual conferences at various locations across India, along with Brahmo leaders such as [[Keshub Chandra Sen|Kesub Chandra Sen]], [[Debendranath Tagore]], Sivanath Sastri, [[Rabindranath Tagore]], [[R. G. Bhandarkar]], and others. In 1888, he obtained a medical degree with honors and entered into [[Public service|government service]]. After that, he worked as a [[medic]] in several hospitals across South India and as a medical lecturer. He also served as a magistrate during the [[British rule]] in Malabar.\n\nGopalan married Kallat Kausallyaammal on 30&nbsp;December 1894. According to the rituals involved, this was the first Brahmo wedding. Ramakrishna Gobal Bhandhakar, a Brahmo leader and social reformer at that time, conducted the wedding at the Madras Brahmo Samaj. Several Brahmo leaders presided over the wedding. Kallat Kausallyaammal was a supporter of Gopalan and assisted his social reform activities.\n\nGopalan worked as a doctor, chief surgeon, and [[Chief physician|superintendent]] at several hospitals in [[South India]], including in [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]], [[Tiruchirappalli|Tiruchirapalli]], [[Madurai]], [[Chennai]], [[Mysore]], and [[Bangalore]] ([[Bowring & Lady Curzon Hospitals]]). He returned to Kerala in 1896 and joined [[Kuthiravattam Mental Hospital|Calicut Lunatic asylum]] (now the Kuthiravattom Mental Hospital) as its first superintendent. Meanwhile, [[caste]] and [[racial discrimination]], evil practices, beliefs, and social injustices were prevalent in Kerala, and atrocities against women and children were at their peak. Gopalan extended his reform ideologies and propagated his reform activities by establishing Brahmo Samaj<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brahmoism; or, History of reformed Hinduism from its origin in 1830, |last=Bose, Ram Chandra.|date=1884|publisher=Funk & Wagnalls|oclc=1032604831}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Brahmo-Samaj|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebrahmosamaj.net|title=brahmosamajnet|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebrahmosamaj.net/history/history.html|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adaniel.tripod.com/brahmosamaj.htm|title=brahmosamaj|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> on 17&nbsp;January 1898 at [[Kozhikode|Calicut]]. To conduct Samaj meetings and prayers, a separate Brahmomandir (hall), now the Ayathan Gopalan Memorial School, Calicut, was opened to the public on 17&nbsp;October 1900. The Brahmomandir was inaugurated by [[Zamorin of Calicut|Mana Vikraman Ettan Thampuran]], the Zamorin King<ref>{{Cite book|title=The zamorins of Calicut: from the earliest times down to A.D. 1806|last=Krishna Ayyar, K. V., 1894-|date=1999|publisher=Publication Division, University of Calicut|oclc=607834506}}</ref> of Calicut. The second branch of Brahmo Samaj was established at [[Alappuzha]] in 1924. A Brahmomandir was also constructed in 1928 at: Poonthoppu, Kommady, Alappuzha (now Grihalakshmi Gandhi Smaraka Seva Sangam) with the donation by a [[landlord]] ([[Jenmi]]) of Alleppey, named Mangalath Cochoumini Channar. Channar was once a strict follower of [[Narayana Guru|Sree Narayana Guru]], but was later influenced by the reform activities of Gopalan and Brahmo Samaj. His daughter, Mangalath Cochoumini Mandhakinibai, spearheaded the reform activities at Alappuzha Brahmosamaj and was married to Gopalan's third son, Devadath Ayathan. This was the first Brahmo wedding conducted at Alappuzha Brahmo Samaj, which spread the custom of Misra Vivaham all over South Kerala.\n\nIn the year 1900, Gopalan initiated the Sugunavardhini Movement and began his social reform activities. Through this movement, he worked to foster human values in children, protect the rights of women, and provide free education to girls and marginalized sections of society, especially the [[Harijan]] communities in Kerala, that were then ill-treated by the higher castes, such as the [[Brahmin]]s and the [[Nair]]s. He established the Lady Chandhawarkar Elementary School intending to educate girls and the underprivileged section of society. Weekly meetings were conducted at his home, Santhi Ashram. Women, children, and people from all walks of life gathered there to share their sorrows with Gopalan and Kausallyaammal, who worked to address them. Children were offered an opportunity to showcase their talents and skills, and were appreciated during these weekly meetings. Kausallyaammal, along with her daughter-in-law M.C. Mandhakinibai Devadath, united women and the lower sections of the community to help them assert their social rights.\n\nUnlike the [[Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana Yogam|Sree Narayana Dharma Paripalana (SNDP)]], which had been established by Narayana Guru<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sreenarayanaguru.in/|title=narayana guru|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; \u1e62\u0101j\u012b, K. N. (2002). N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru: j\u012bvita\u1e43 kr\u0325tika\u1e37 dar\u015bana\u1e43. Tr\u032e\u015b\u015b\u016br: Kar\u0332ant\u0332 Buks: Distribution Cosmo Books. OCLC 52929384.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; B\u0101lakr\u0325i\u1e63h\u1e47an, P. K. (1969). N\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru (in Malayalam). Kottayam: Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative : Society Ltd. OCLC 31116295.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana, Guru; Nityachaitanya, Yati (2003). That alone, the core of wisdom: a commentary on \u0100tmopade\u015ba \u015batakam, the one hundred verses of self-instruction of Narayana Guru. New Delhi: D.K. Printworld. ISBN 9788124602409. OCLC 915135852.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru (1961). Souvenir to commemorate the 107th birthday of Sree Narayana Guru. Singapore: Sree Narayana Mission. OCLC 498088723.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Narayana Guru; Kesavan Vaidyar, C. R (1990). \u015ar\u0332\u012bn\u0101r\u0101ya\u1e47aguru Svantha\u1e43 Vachana\u1e45ga\u1e37iloode (in Malayalam). K\u014d\u1e6d\u1e6daya\u1e43: \u1e0ci. \u1e62i. Buks: Distributors, Current Books. OCLC 27111533|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=A prophet of peace or Sree Narayana Gurudev of labor (a study).|last=Theerthan, Swami Dharma.|date=1933|publisher=The City Press|oclc=78599841}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Garland of visions : Dar\u015banam\u0101l\u0101 of Narayana Guru|last=Narayana Guru, 1856-1928.|date=2007|publisher=D.K. Printworld|isbn=978-8124603918|oclc=167576536}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Narayana Guru|doi = 10.1163/2212-5019_beh_com_9000000256}}</ref> and was influential around the same time, the Sugunavardhini Movement and Brahmo Samaj were composed mostly of professionals and intellectuals, including Brahmananda Swamisivayogi, Vagbhatananda Guru, and Brahmavadi P. Kunhiraman, all with a more secular approach to reform. Other eminent personalities who worked with Brahmo Samaj Calicut were: G. Subbha Rao, Kallingal Madathil Rarichan Mooppan, Kunjikoru Mooppan, C. Achuthan Vakeel, B.S.T. Mudaliyar, Rao Bahadur V. V. Govindan, Kallat Raghavan, Swami Aryabhadhan, Swami Brahmavradhan, Padmanabha Panikar, Sadhu Sivaprasad, Rama Sasthrikal, Manjeri Ramayyar, [[Mithavaadi Krishnan|Mithavadi C. Krishnan]], Lady Chandhawarkar, Rabindranath Tagore, Kesub Chandrasen, [[Rajnarayan Basu|Raj Narayan Basu]], [[Ramananda Chatterjee|Ramananda Chatterji]], Debjyothi Burman, Sasi Bhushan Basu, Satishchandra Chakraborthi, Jatheendrakumar Majumdar, and [[Mahadev Govind Ranade|Justice Ranade]]. In addition to uplifting the underprivileged and the marginalized, and educating women and [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|the underprivileged]], their movement led to several reforms, such as Misra Vivaham and Misra Bhojanam. Dr. Gopalan also took part in the Thali Road strike (Samaram at Calicut).\n\nOn 17&nbsp;November 1917, Gopalan was honored by the British Government with the highest civilian award and title, [[Rai Sahib|Rao Sahib]],<ref>\"British India: INDIAN TITLE BADGE (MYB # 327), RAO BAHADUR & RAO SAHIB MEDALS\". worldofcoins.eu. Retrieved 2014-10-18.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omsa.org/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=65&size=big&cat=|title=rai sahib|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omsa.org/photopost/showphoto.php?photo=65&size=big&cat=|title=medal|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldofcoins.eu/forum/index.php?topic=21524.0|title=rao sahib|website=|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Introduction to the Constitution of India By Sharma, Sharma B.k.. 2007. p. 83.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Kaur, Madanjit (2008). Maharaja Ranjit Singh. Unistar Books. ISBN 9788189899547.|year=|isbn=|url-status=live}}</ref> for his social and humanitarian services.\n\nHe passed away on 2&nbsp;May 1948, at the age of 87.\n\n==Works==\nGopalan translated the Bible of Brahmosamaj, [[Brahmo Dharma|Brahmodharma]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The offering. [Reprinted on the occasion of the centenary celebration of Maharshideva's initiation into the Brahma Dharma].|last=\u1e6ch\u0101kura, Debendran\u0101tha, 1817-1905.|date=c. 1943|oclc=910095}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hatcher|first=Brian A.|title=Debendranath Tagore and the Tattvabodhin\u012b Sabh\u0101|date=2008-01-01|work=Bourgeouis Hinduism, or Faith of the Modern Vedantists|pages=33\u201348|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195326086|doi=10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195326086.003.0003}}</ref> initially  written in the [[Bengali language]] by Maharshi Debendranath Tagore, to Malayalam in 1910. He also wrote many songs and [[Kirtan|keerthanams]] to be sung during [[Brahmoism|Brahmosamaj prayer]] meetings. He propagated his reform ideologies through drama, public awareness, and his writings. ''Saranjiniparinayam'', ''Susheeladukham'' (musical drama), and ''Plaguefarse'' were among his famous dramas performed by the [[Vaidyaratnam P. S. Warrier|Kottakkal P. S. Warrier]] Nadaka Sangam throughout Kerala for many years. His other literary contributions are listed below:\n\n* ''Brahmadharmam''\n* ''Keerthanaratnamala''\n* ''Brahmamatham''\n* ''Rammohunroy (Harikatha)''\n* ''Madhaaikyam''\n* ''Madhavum Guruvum''\n* ''Madhavan''\n* ''Aaradhanayude Randu Padikal''\n* ''Brahma Madhavum Ithara Madhangalum''\n* ''Jaathi''\n* ''Plague Farse'' (drama)\n* ''Vivaahageethangal''\n* ''Saranjiniparinayam'' (musical drama)\n* ''Susheeladukham'' (musical drama)\n* ''Jai Britannia''\n* ''Yeshu Daivamayirunnuvo''\n* ''British Bharana Mahathmyam''\n* ''Ente Ammayude Ormadaykk'' (biography of mother Kallat Chiruthammal)''\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Dr. Ayyathan Gopalan  ''Malayalam Memoir'' (2013) edited by V.R.Govindhanunni published by Mathrubhumi books, Kozhikode\n* Kesava Menon. K. P. (1974). ''Samakaleenaraya Chila Keraleeyar''. Sahithya Pra. Co. s: Sahithya Pra. Co. s. p.&nbsp;239\n* Kausallya Gopalan (1932) Biography written by [[Vagbhatananda]] guru, published by Mathrubhumi Press, Calicut in 1932\n* ''Mughaparichayam'' (1959) Govindan A.C. Published by K.R.Brothers, Kozhikkode. p.&nbsp;155 p.&nbsp;156 p.&nbsp;157 p.&nbsp;158 p.&nbsp;159\n* ''Ente ammayude ormadaykk'' (1901) Biography of Kallat Chiruthammal, written by DR.Ayathan Gopalan.\n* Prof. Sreedharan Menon .A. (1967). ''A Survey of Kerala History''. Kottayam: Sahitya Pravarthaka Co-operative Society [Sales Dept.]; National Book Stall.\n* Prof.Sreedharamenon .A. (1987) ''Kerala History and its Makers'', Kottayam; National bookstall\n* [[K. K. N. Kurup|Kurup, K. K. N.]] (1988), ''Modern Kerala: Studies in Social and Agrarian Relations'', Mittal Publications, {{ISBN|9788170990949}}\n* [[Vagbhatananda#CITEREFKurup1988|Kurup (1988)]], p.&nbsp;94\n* [[K. K. N. Kurup|Kurup, K. K. N.]] (September 1988). \"Peasantry and the Anti-Imperialist Struggles in Kerala\". ''Social Scientist''. '''16''' (9): 35\u201345. {{doi|10.2307/3517171}}. {{JSTOR|3517171}}.\n* Biography of Brahmanada Sivayogi written by K Bheeman Nair ''Asathyathil ninnu sathyathilekku''(\u0d05\u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d47\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d )\n* ''Biography of Brahmananda Swami Sivayogy'' by A K Nair\n* ''Brahmananda Swami Sivayogi'' by Pavana\n*''Journal of Indian history'', University of Kerela Press, 2001 p270\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayyathan Gopalan}}\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Brahmoism]]\n[[Category:Indian medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Indian writers]]\n[[Category:People from Kerala]]\n[[Category:People from Thalassery]]\n[[Category:Reform movements]]\n[[Category:Social reformers]]\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "restore to last undamaged version; rv tests/nonimprovement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayyathan_Gopalan"}
{"title_page": "Clarivate Analytics", "text_new": "{{short description|American analytics company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Clarivate\n| logo_padding        = \n| image               = 1500 Spring Garden.jpg\n| image_size          = 230px\n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = Clarivate Headquarters at 1500 Spring Garden Street in Philadelphia\n| type                = Public company\n| traded_as           = {{Unbulleted list\n| {{NYSE|CCC}}\n}}\n| ISIN                = \n| industry            = [[Analytics]]\n| predecessor         = The Intellectual Property and Science business of [[Thomson Reuters]]\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|2016}}\n| founder             = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location         = \n| hq_location_city    = [[Philadelphia]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| num_locations       = \n| num_locations_year  = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served         = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people          = Jerre Stead (CEO)\n| products            = \n| brands              = \n| production          = \n| production_year     = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services            = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income    = \n| income_year         = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income          = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year     = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| aum                 = <!-- Only for financial-service companies -->\n| assets              = \n| assets_year         = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity              = \n| equity_year         = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| owners              = \n| members             = \n| members_year        = <!-- Year of members data (if known) -->\n| num_employees       = \n| num_employees_year  = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent              = \n| divisions           = \n| subsid              = \n| module              = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| ratio               = <!-- Basel III ratio, for BANKS ONLY -->\n| rating              = <!-- credit rating, for BANKS ONLY -->\n| website             = {{URL|https://clarivate.com/}}\n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\n'''Clarivate''' is a Philadelphia and London-based company formed in 2016, following the acquisition of [[Thomson Reuters]]' Intellectual Property and Science Business by [[Onex Corporation]] and [[Baring Private Equity Asia]].<ref name=\"Clarivate Onex\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Acquisition of the Thomson Reuters Intellectual Property and Science business by Onex and Baring Asia completed | agency=PR Newswire | date=2016-10-03 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/acquisition-of-the-thomson-reuters-intellectual-property-and-science-business-by-onex-and-baring-asia-completed-300337402.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> In May 13, 2019, Clarivate merged with Churchill Capital.<ref name=\"Clarivate Churchill\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Churchill Capital Corp Completes Merger with Clarivate Analytics Plc | agency=PR Newswire | date=2016-10-03 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/churchill-capital-corp-completes-merger-with-clarivate-analytics-plc-300848873.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\nClarivate owns and operates a collection of [[subscription business model|subscription-based]] services focused largely on [[analytics]], including scientific and academic research, [[patent]] intelligence and compliance standards, pharmaceutical and biotech intelligence [[trademark]], domain and [[brand]] protection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-491848243/clarivate-analytics-new-name-established-products|title=\"Clarivate Analytics: New Name, Established Products\" by Ojala, Marydee - Online Searcher, Vol. 41, Issue 3, May-June 2017 {{!}} Online Research Library: Questia|website=www.questia.com|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> The services include [[Web of Science]], Cortellis, Derwent, [[Derwent World Patents Index]], CompuMark, [[MarkMonitor]], Techstreet, [[Publons]], [[EndNote]], [[Kopernio]], and [[ScholarOne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-491848243/clarivate-analytics-new-name-established-products|title=\"Clarivate Analytics: New Name, Established Products\" by Ojala, Marydee - Online Searcher, Vol. 41, Issue 3, May-June 2017 {{!}} Online Research Library: Questia|website=www.questia.com|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\n== Company history ==\nClarivate was formerly the Intellectual Property and Science division of [[Thomson Reuters]]. In 2016, Thomson Reuters struck a $3.55 billion deal in which they [[corporate spin-off|spun it off]] into an independent company, and sold it to private-equity firms [[Onex Corporation]] and Baring Private Equity Asia.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Bob |last=Grant |url=https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/46558/title/Web-of-Science-Sold-for-More-Than--3-Billion/ |title=Web of Science sold for more than $3 billion|website=The Scientist |date=2016-07-15 |access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref name=\"Analytics 2016\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Acquisition of the Thomson Reuters Intellectual Property and Science business by Onex and Baring Asia completed | agency=PR Newswire | date=2016-10-03 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/acquisition-of-the-thomson-reuters-intellectual-property-and-science-business-by-onex-and-baring-asia-completed-300337402.html | access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n\nIn May 13, 2019, Clarivate merged with Churchill Capital. Churchill's CEO, Jerre Stead (previous chairman and CEO of [[IHS Markit]])<ref>{{cite news |title=DTN names Jerre Stead and Sheryl von Blucher as co-CEOs |url= https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dtn-names-jerre-stead-and-sheryl-von-blucher-as-co-ceos-300588160.html |newspaper=PR Newswire |date=2018-01-25 |accessdate=2019-04-03}}</ref> became Clarivate's executive chairman.<ref name=Singh>{{cite news |last=Singh |first=Vandana |date=2019-01-14 |title=Churchill Capital to merge with Clarivate Analytics |url= https://seekingalpha.com/news/3422724-churchill-capital-merge-clarivate-analytics |work=Seeking Alpha |location= |access-date=2019-01-16 }}</ref>\n\n== Products and services ==\n=== Web of Science Group ===\nProducts providing data, analytics, insights, workflow tools, and professional services to researchers, universities, research institutions, governments, private and public research funding organizations, publishers, and research-intensive corporations,<ref>[https://clarivate.com/webofsciencegroup/ Web of Science Group]</ref> including:\n* [[Web of Science]] Platform\n* [[EndNote]]\n* InCites\n* Journal Citation Reports\n* Essential Science Indicators\n* ScholarOne\n* [[Publons]]\n* Converis\n* [[Kopernio]]\n\n=== Cortellis ===\nSuite of life science intelligence solutions used to inform decision making across the drug and device development lifecycle,<ref>[https://clarivate.com/cortellis/ Cortellis]</ref> including:\n* Cortellis Regulatory Intelligence\n* Cortellis Competitive Intelligence\n* Cortellis Clinical Trials Intelligence\n* Cortellis Deals Intelligence\n* Cortellis Drug Discovery Intelligence\n* Cortellis Digital Health Intelligence\n* MetaCore, a Cortellis Solution\n* Newport, a Cortellis Solution\n* BioWorld\n\n===  Derwent ===\nDatabase products and services used for searching and analyzing patents; IP administration and prosecution support services to support the IP lifecycle,<ref>[https://clarivate.com/derwent/ Derwent]</ref> including: \n* Derwent Innovation\n* [[Derwent World Patents Index]]\n* Derwent SequenceBase\n* Derwent Data Analyzer\n* GENESEQ\n\n=== CompuMark ===\nInformation services used by brand and trademark professionals to evaluate new potential trademarks and monitor existing trademarks for infringement,<ref>[https://clarivate.com/compumark/ CompuMark]</ref> including:\n* SAEGIS Trademark Screening Tools\n* TM go365 DIY Research Solution\n* Trademark Full Search, Trademark Watching\n* Copyright and Title Searches\n\n=== MarkMonitor ===\nProprietary software and services for registering and managing the domain name portfolios, providing online brand protection, antipiracy and antifraud solutions,<ref>[https://markmonitor.com/ MarkMonitor]</ref> including:\n* MarkMonitor Domain Management\n* MarkMonitor AntiCounterfeiting\n* MarkMonitor AntiPiracy\n* MarkMonitor AntiFraud\n\n=== Techstreet ===\nEngineering industry standards, codes, and management tools for staying compliant in electronic, print and enterprise solutions,<ref>[https://clarivate.com/techstreet/ TechStreet]</ref> including:\n* Techstreet Enterprise\n* Techstreet Store\n\n== Annual lists, reports and more ==\n=== Highly Cited Researchers ===\nClarivate publishes an annual Highly Cited Researchers list. The list recognizes \"the world's most influential researchers of the past decade, demonstrated by the production of multiple highly-cited papers that rank in the top 1% by citations for field and year in [[Web of Science]].\"<ref>[https://recognition.webofsciencegroup.com/awards/highly-cited/2019/ Web of Science Highly Cited Researchers 2019]</ref> Researchers are selected for their exceptional performance in one or more of 21 fields (those used in Clarivate Essential Science Indicators, or ESI) or across several fields. The 2019 list of Highly Cited Researchers was released on November 19, 2019.<ref name=\"Clarivate Highly Cited Researchers 2019\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Global Highly Cited Researchers 2019 list reveals top talent in the sciences and social sciences | agency=PR Newswire | date=2019-11-19 | url=https://clarivate.com/news/global-highly-cited-researchers-2019-list-reveals-top-talent-in-the-sciences-and-social-sciences/ | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Citation Laureates ===\nEach year since 2002, [[Institute for Scientific Information]] analysts have drawn on [[Web of Science]] publication and citation data to identify influential researchers in the research areas recognized by Nobel Prizes: [[Physiology]] or [[Medicine]], [[Physics]], [[Chemistry]] and [[Economics]]. Out of some 47 million papers indexed in the [[Web of Science]] since 1970, only 4,900 (or .01%) have been cited 2,000 or more times. It is from the authors of this group of papers that Citation Laureates are identified and selected. The 2019 Citation Laureates were named on September 24, 2019.<ref name=\"Clarivate Citation Laureates 2019\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=The Web of Science Group Reveals Annual Citation Laureates of 'Nobel Class' | agency=PR Newswire | date=2019-09-24 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-web-of-science-group-reveals-annual-citation-laureates-of-nobel-class-300923373.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Journal Citation Reports ===\nClarivate publishes the annual [[Journal Citation Reports]], which identifies the world's most impactful academic journals included in the Science Citation Index Expanded (SCIE) and Social Sciences Citation Index (SSCI), part of the [[Web of Science]] Core Collection. The 2019 [[Journal Citation Reports]] was released on June 20, 2019.<ref name=\"Clarivate Journal Citation Reports 2019\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=The Web of Science Group\u202fReleases 2019 Journal Citation Reports, Revealing the World's Most Influential Journals| agency=PR Newswire | date=2019-06-20 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-web-of-science-group-releases-2019-journal-citation-reports-revealing-the-worlds-most-influential-journals-300871565.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Drugs to Watch ===\nThe annual Drugs to Watch analysis, produced since 2013, identifies new [[drugs]] forecasted to achieve annual sales of $1 billion or more by 2023 using data and analytics from Cortellis life sciences solutions. The 2019 Drugs to Watch report] was released on March 20, 2019 and included drugs [[Upadacitinib]], [[Zolgensma]] and [[Skyrizi]]<ref name=\"Clarivate Drugs to Watch 2019\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Pharmaceutical Collaborations and Rare Diseases Drive the Drugs to Watch as New Blockbusters Are Forecast to Hit the Market in 2019 | agency=PR Newswire | date=2019-03-20 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/in/news-releases/pharmaceutical-collaborations-and-rare-diseases-drive-the-drugs-to-watch-as-new-blockbusters-are-forecast-to-hit-the-market-in-2019-887083660.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n== Acquisitions ==\n* January 17, 2020: Decision Resources Group, a leading healthcare research and consulting company, providing high-value healthcare industry analysis and insights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clarivate.com/news/clarivate-analytics-to-acquire-decision-resources-group-creating-a-leading-global-provider-of-data-driven-solutions-to-the-life-sciences-industry/|title=Clarivate to acquire Decision Resources Group|last=January 17|last2=2020January 17|date=2020-01-17|website=Clarivate Analytics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17|last3=2020}}</ref>\n* December 2, 2019: Darts-ip, provider of case law data and analytics for intellectual property (IP) professionals.<ref name=\"Clarivate Darts-ip\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Clarivate Analytics has Acquired Leading Provider of Intellectual Property Case Law and Analytics Darts-ip | agency=PR Newswire | date=2019-12-02 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/clarivate-analytics-has-acquired-leading-provider-of-intellectual-property-case-law-and-analytics-darts-ip-300966595.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n* September 9, 2019: [[SequenceBase]], provider of patent sequence information and search technology to the biotech, pharmaceutical and chemical industries.<ref name=\"Clarivate SequenceBase\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Clarivate Analytics acquires the SequenceBase business to expand its search and analysis capabilities for the life sciences IP market | agency=PR Newswire | date=2019-09-09 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/clarivate-analytics-acquires-the-sequencebase-business-to-expand-its-search-and-analysis-capabilities-for-the-life-sciences-ip-market-300913749.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n* October 30, 2018: TrademarkVision, provider of Artificial Intelligence (AI) trademark research solutions.<ref name=\"Clarivate TrademarkVision\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Clarivate Analytics to enhance AI-driven trademark research solutions with TrademarkVision acquisition | agency=PR Newswire | date=2018-10-30 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/clarivate-analytics-to-enhance-ai-driven-trademark-research-solutions-with-trademarkvision-acquisition-300740793.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n* April 10, 2018: [[Kopernio]], AI-tech startup providing ability to search for full-text versions of selected scientific journal articles.<ref name=\"Clarivate Kopernio\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | publisher=Clarivate Analytics | title=Clarivate Analytics Acquires Research Startup Kopernio to Accelerate Pace of Scientific Innovation | agency=PR Newswire | date=2018-04-10 | url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/clarivate-analytics-acquires-research-startup-kopernio-to-accelerate-pace-of-scientific-innovation-300626878.html | access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n* June 1, 2017: [[Publons]], a global platform for researchers to share recognition for peer review.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Page|first1=Benedicte|title=Clarivate Analytics buys Publons|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/clarivate-analytics-buys-publons-562691|access-date=2019-12-03|work=The Bookseller}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Analytics companies]]\n[[Category:Bibliometrics]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2018]]\n[[Category:Business services companies established in 2018]]\n[[Category:2018 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Private equity portfolio companies]]\n[[Category:Clarivate Analytics| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American analytics company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Clarivate\n| logo                = Clarivate Analytics.svg\n| logo_size           = 225px\n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| logo_padding        = \n| image               = 1500 Spring Garden.jpg\n| image_size          = 230px\n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = Clarivate Headquarters at 1500 Spring Garden Street in Philadelphia\n| type                = Public company\n| traded_as           = {{Unbulleted list\n| {{NYSE|CCC}}\n}}\n| ISIN                = \n| industry            = [[Analytics]]\n| predecessor         = The Intellectual Property and Science business of [[Thomson Reuters]]\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|2016}}\n| founder             = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location         = \n| hq_location_city    = [[Philadelphia]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States]]\n| num_locations       = \n| num_locations_year  = <!-- Year of num_locations data (